[{"text": "What does it mean to have a Bitcoin?", "start": 3.9, "duration": 2.58}, {"text": "Many people have heard of Bitcoin, that it's a fully digital currency", "start": 7.42, "duration": 3.838}, {"text": "with no government to issue it, that no banks need to manage accounts", "start": 11.258, "duration": 3.893}, {"text": "and verify transactions, and that no one really knows who invented it.", "start": 15.151, "duration": 3.949}, {"text": "And yet many people don't know the answer to this question, at least not in full.", "start": 19.38, "duration": 3.9}, {"text": "To get there, and to make sure that the technical details underlying", "start": 24.1, "duration": 3.713}, {"text": "the answer actually feel motivated, we're going to walk through,", "start": 27.813, "duration": 3.55}, {"text": "step by step, how you might have invented your own version of Bitcoin.", "start": 31.363, "duration": 3.877}, {"text": "We'll start with you keeping track of payments with your friends using a communal ledger,", "start": 36.14, "duration": 4.36}, {"text": "and then as you start to trust your friends and the world around you less and less,", "start": 40.5, "duration": 4.116}, {"text": "and if you're clever enough to bring in a few ideas from cryptography to help circumvent", "start": 44.616, "duration": 4.36}, {"text": "the need for trust, what you end up with is what's called a cryptocurrency.", "start": 48.976, "duration": 3.724}, {"text": "Bitcoin is just the first implemented example of a cryptocurrency,", "start": 53.84, "duration": 4.082}, {"text": "and now there are thousands more on exchanges with traditional currencies.", "start": 57.922, "duration": 4.638}, {"text": "Walking the path of inventing your own can help to set the foundations", "start": 63.3, "duration": 3.387}, {"text": "for understanding some of the more recent players in the game,", "start": 66.687, "duration": 3.049}, {"text": "and recognizing when and why there's room for different design choices.", "start": 69.736, "duration": 3.484}, {"text": "In fact, one of the reasons I chose this topic is that in the last year there's", "start": 74.1, "duration": 4.633}, {"text": "been a huge amount of attention, investment, and hype directed at these currencies.", "start": 78.733, "duration": 4.927}, {"text": "I'm not going to comment or speculate on the current or future exchange rates,", "start": 84.28, "duration": 4.047}, {"text": "but I think we'd all agree that anyone looking to buy a cryptocurrency should really", "start": 88.327, "duration": 4.411}, {"text": "know what it is.", "start": 92.738, "duration": 0.882}, {"text": "And I don't just mean in terms of analogies with vague connections to gold mining,", "start": 93.92, "duration": 4.587}, {"text": "I mean an actual direct description of what the computers are doing when we send,", "start": 98.507, "duration": 4.587}, {"text": "receive, and create cryptocurrencies.", "start": 103.094, "duration": 2.126}, {"text": "One thing worth stressing is that even though you and I are going to dig into the", "start": 106.3, "duration": 4.228}, {"text": "details here, and that takes meaningful time,", "start": 110.528, "duration": 2.401}, {"text": "you don't actually need to know those details if you just want to use the", "start": 112.929, "duration": 3.863}, {"text": "cryptocurrency, just like you don't need to know the details of what happens", "start": 116.792, "duration": 4.019}, {"text": "under the hood when you swipe a credit card.", "start": 120.811, "duration": 2.349}, {"text": "Like any digital payment, there's lots of user-friendly applications that let", "start": 123.72, "duration": 3.723}, {"text": "you just send and receive the currencies without thinking about what's going on.", "start": 127.443, "duration": 3.917}, {"text": "The difference is that the backbone underlying this is not a bank that", "start": 131.66, "duration": 4.273}, {"text": "verifies transactions, instead it's a clever system of decentralized", "start": 135.933, "duration": 4.213}, {"text": "trustless verification based on some of the math born in cryptography.", "start": 140.146, "duration": 4.334}, {"text": "But to start I want you to actually set aside the thought", "start": 145.9, "duration": 2.29}, {"text": "of cryptocurrencies and all that just for a few minutes.", "start": 148.19, "duration": 2.29}, {"text": "We're going to begin the story with something more down to earth,", "start": 151.08, "duration": 2.881}, {"text": "ledgers and digital signatures.", "start": 153.961, "duration": 1.419}, {"text": "If you and your friends exchange money pretty frequently,", "start": 156.34, "duration": 2.893}, {"text": "paying your share of the dinner bill and such,", "start": 159.233, "duration": 2.386}, {"text": "it can be inconvenient to exchange cash all the time.", "start": 161.619, "duration": 2.741}, {"text": "So you might keep a communal ledger that records all the", "start": 164.72, "duration": 2.656}, {"text": "payments you intend to make at some point in the future.", "start": 167.376, "duration": 2.704}, {"text": "Alice pays Bob $20, Bob pays Charlie $40, things like that.", "start": 170.62, "duration": 4.48}, {"text": "This ledger is going to be something public and accessible to everyone,", "start": 175.5, "duration": 3.544}, {"text": "like a website where anyone can go and add new lines.", "start": 179.044, "duration": 2.696}, {"text": "And let's say at the end of every month you all get together,", "start": 182.48, "duration": 3.028}, {"text": "look at the list of transactions, and settle up.", "start": 185.508, "duration": 2.432}, {"text": "If you spent more than you received, you put that money in the pot,", "start": 188.28, "duration": 3.083}, {"text": "and if you received more than you spent, you take that money out.", "start": 191.363, "duration": 3.037}, {"text": "So the protocol for being part of this very simple system might look like this.", "start": 195.46, "duration": 3.9}, {"text": "Anyone can add lines to the ledger, and at the end", "start": 200.02, "duration": 2.644}, {"text": "of every month you all get together and settle up.", "start": 202.664, "duration": 2.696}, {"text": "Now one problem with a public ledger like this is that anyone can add a line.", "start": 206.3, "duration": 4.46}, {"text": "So what's to prevent Bob from going and writing", "start": 211.02, "duration": 3.014}, {"text": "Alice pays Bob $100 without Alice approving?", "start": 214.034, "duration": 2.886}, {"text": "How are we supposed to trust that all of these", "start": 217.78, "duration": 2.57}, {"text": "transactions are what the sender meant them to be?", "start": 220.35, "duration": 2.85}, {"text": "Well this is where the first bit of cryptography comes in, digital signatures.", "start": 224.58, "duration": 3.96}, {"text": "Like handwritten signatures, the idea here is that Alice should be able to add", "start": 229.48, "duration": 4.312}, {"text": "something next to that transaction that proves that she has seen it and that she's", "start": 233.792, "duration": 4.589}, {"text": "approved of it, and it should be infeasible for anyone else to forge that signature.", "start": 238.381, "duration": 4.699}, {"text": "At first, it might seem like a digital signature shouldn't even be possible.", "start": 244.3, "duration": 4.28}, {"text": "I mean, whatever data makes up that signature can just be read and copied by a computer.", "start": 249.22, "duration": 4.64}, {"text": "So how do you prevent forgeries?", "start": 254.4, "duration": 1.74}, {"text": "Well the way this works is that everyone generates what's called a public", "start": 257.32, "duration": 3.541}, {"text": "key-private key pair, each of which looks like some string of bits.", "start": 260.861, "duration": 3.299}, {"text": "The private key is sometimes also called a secret key,", "start": 264.8, "duration": 2.808}, {"text": "so we can abbreviate it as SK while abbreviating the public key as PK.", "start": 267.608, "duration": 3.692}, {"text": "As the name suggests, this secret key is something you want to keep to yourself.", "start": 272.34, "duration": 3.88}, {"text": "In the real world, your handwritten signature looks", "start": 277.06, "duration": 2.377}, {"text": "the same no matter what document you're signing.", "start": 279.437, "duration": 2.283}, {"text": "But a digital signature is actually much stronger,", "start": 282.28, "duration": 2.505}, {"text": "because it changes for different messages.", "start": 284.785, "duration": 2.155}, {"text": "It looks like some string of 1s and 0s, commonly something like 256 bits,", "start": 287.84, "duration": 4.777}, {"text": "and altering the message even slightly completely changes what", "start": 292.617, "duration": 4.122}, {"text": "the signature on that message should look like.", "start": 296.739, "duration": 3.141}, {"text": "Speaking a little more formally, producing a signature involves a", "start": 300.84, "duration": 3.601}, {"text": "function that depends both on the message itself and on your private key.", "start": 304.441, "duration": 4.099}, {"text": "The private key ensures that only you can produce that signature,", "start": 309.2, "duration": 3.445}, {"text": "and the fact that it depends on the message means that no one can", "start": 312.645, "duration": 3.497}, {"text": "just copy one of your signatures and forge it on another message.", "start": 316.142, "duration": 3.498}, {"text": "Hand-in-hand with this is a second function used to verify that a signature is valid,", "start": 321.0, "duration": 4.546}, {"text": "and this is where the public key comes into play.", "start": 325.546, "duration": 2.674}, {"text": "All it does is output true or false to indicate if this was a signature produced", "start": 329.2, "duration": 4.253}, {"text": "by the private key associated with the public key you're using for verification.", "start": 333.453, "duration": 4.307}, {"text": "I won't go into the details of how exactly both these functions work,", "start": 338.64, "duration": 3.954}, {"text": "but the idea is that it should be completely infeasible to", "start": 342.594, "duration": 3.38}, {"text": "find a valid signature if you don't know the secret key.", "start": 345.974, "duration": 3.266}, {"text": "Specifically, there's no strategy better than just guessing and checking random", "start": 350.06, "duration": 4.007}, {"text": "signatures, which you can check using the public key that everyone knows.", "start": 354.067, "duration": 3.753}, {"text": "Now think about how many signatures there are with a length of 256 bits.", "start": 358.98, "duration": 4.22}, {"text": "That's 2 to the power of 256!", "start": 363.84, "duration": 2.34}, {"text": "This is a stupidly large number.", "start": 367.14, "duration": 2.42}, {"text": "To call it astronomically large would be giving way too much credit to astronomy.", "start": 369.86, "duration": 3.78}, {"text": "In fact, I made a supplemental video devoted just", "start": 374.26, "duration": 2.856}, {"text": "to illustrating what a huge number this is.", "start": 377.116, "duration": 2.564}, {"text": "Right here, let's just say that when you verify that a signature against a given message", "start": 380.38, "duration": 4.796}, {"text": "is valid, you can feel extremely confident that the only way someone could have produced", "start": 385.176, "duration": 4.85}, {"text": "it is if they knew the secret key associated with the public key you used for", "start": 390.026, "duration": 4.251}, {"text": "verification.", "start": 394.277, "duration": 0.763}, {"text": "Making sure people sign transactions on the ledger is pretty good,", "start": 397.12, "duration": 3.387}, {"text": "but there's one slight loophole.", "start": 400.507, "duration": 1.693}, {"text": "If Alice signs a transaction like Alice pays Bob $100,", "start": 402.72, "duration": 3.306}, {"text": "even though Bob can't forge Alice's signature on a new message,", "start": 406.026, "duration": 3.919}, {"text": "he could just copy that same line as many times as he wants.", "start": 409.945, "duration": 3.735}, {"text": "I mean, that message-signature combination remains valid.", "start": 414.3, "duration": 2.92}, {"text": "To get around this, we make it so that when you sign a transaction,", "start": 417.92, "duration": 4.073}, {"text": "the message has to include some sort of unique ID associated with that transaction.", "start": 421.993, "duration": 5.107}, {"text": "That way, if Alice pays Bob $100 multiple times,", "start": 427.84, "duration": 2.942}, {"text": "each one of those lines on the ledger requires a completely new signature.", "start": 430.782, "duration": 4.598}, {"text": "Alright, great. Digital signatures remove a huge aspect of trust in this initial protocol.", "start": 436.76, "duration": 5.18}, {"text": "But even still, if you were to really do this,", "start": 442.38, "duration": 2.348}, {"text": "you would be relying on an honor system of sorts.", "start": 444.728, "duration": 2.552}, {"text": "Namely, you're trusting that everyone will actually follow", "start": 447.72, "duration": 2.554}, {"text": "through and settle up in cash at the end of each month.", "start": 450.274, "duration": 2.466}, {"text": "What if, for example, Charlie racks up thousands", "start": 453.56, "duration": 2.96}, {"text": "of dollars in debt and just refuses to show up?", "start": 456.52, "duration": 2.96}, {"text": "The only real reason to revert back to cash to settle up is if some people,", "start": 460.12, "duration": 4.366}, {"text": "I'm looking at you Charlie, owe a lot of money.", "start": 464.486, "duration": 2.794}, {"text": "So maybe you have the clever idea that you never actually have to settle up in cash as", "start": 467.86, "duration": 4.276}, {"text": "long as you have some way to prevent people from spending too much more than they take", "start": 472.136, "duration": 4.325}, {"text": "in.", "start": 476.461, "duration": 0.199}, {"text": "Maybe you start by having everyone pay $100 into the pot,", "start": 477.34, "duration": 3.722}, {"text": "and then have the first few lines of the ledger read Alice gets $100, Bob gets $100,", "start": 481.062, "duration": 5.551}, {"text": "Charlie gets $100, etc.", "start": 486.613, "duration": 1.567}, {"text": "Now, just don't accept any transactions where someone", "start": 489.02, "duration": 3.394}, {"text": "is spending more than they already have on that ledger.", "start": 492.414, "duration": 3.586}, {"text": "For example, if the first two transactions are Charlie pays Alice $50", "start": 496.84, "duration": 4.99}, {"text": "and Charlie pays Bob $50, if he would have tried to add Charlie pays you $20,", "start": 501.83, "duration": 5.641}, {"text": "that would be invalid, as invalid as if he had never signed it.", "start": 507.471, "duration": 4.629}, {"text": "Notice, this means verifying a transaction requires", "start": 512.94, "duration": 3.041}, {"text": "knowing the full history of transactions up to that point.", "start": 515.981, "duration": 3.519}, {"text": "This is also going to be true in cryptocurrencies,", "start": 520.16, "duration": 2.959}, {"text": "though there is a little room for optimization.", "start": 523.119, "duration": 2.841}, {"text": "What's interesting here is that this step removes the", "start": 528.38, "duration": 3.327}, {"text": "connection between the ledger and actual physical US dollars.", "start": 531.707, "duration": 3.893}, {"text": "In theory, if everyone in the world was using this ledger,", "start": 536.2, "duration": 3.227}, {"text": "you could live your whole life just sending and receiving money", "start": 539.427, "duration": 3.561}, {"text": "on this ledger without ever having to convert to real US dollars.", "start": 542.988, "duration": 3.672}, {"text": "In fact, to emphasize this point, let's start referring to the", "start": 547.58, "duration": 3.367}, {"text": "quantities on the ledger as ledger dollars, or LD for short.", "start": 550.947, "duration": 3.313}, {"text": "You are of course free to exchange ledger dollars for real US dollars.", "start": 554.82, "duration": 3.84}, {"text": "For example, maybe Alice gives Bob a $10 bill in the real world in exchange for him", "start": 559.06, "duration": 5.23}, {"text": "adding and signing the transaction $10 Bob pays Alice $10 to this communal ledger.", "start": 564.29, "duration": 5.23}, {"text": "But exchanges like that are not guaranteed by the protocol.", "start": 570.72, "duration": 3.5}, {"text": "It's now more analogous to how you might exchange dollars", "start": 574.72, "duration": 3.054}, {"text": "for Euros or any other currency on the open market.", "start": 577.774, "duration": 2.786}, {"text": "It's just its own independent thing.", "start": 581.18, "duration": 2.62}, {"text": "This is the first important thing to understand about Bitcoin,", "start": 584.58, "duration": 3.543}, {"text": "or any other cryptocurrency.", "start": 588.123, "duration": 1.657}, {"text": "What it is, is a ledger.", "start": 589.78, "duration": 2.64}, {"text": "The history of transactions is the currency.", "start": 593.18, "duration": 2.8}, {"text": "Of course, with Bitcoin, money doesn't enter the ledger with people buying in using cash.", "start": 597.16, "duration": 4.4}, {"text": "I'll get to how new money enters the ledger in just a few minutes.", "start": 602.0, "duration": 2.82}, {"text": "But before that, there's actually an even more significant difference", "start": 605.54, "duration": 3.255}, {"text": "between our current system of ledger dollars and how cryptocurrencies work.", "start": 608.795, "duration": 3.585}, {"text": "So far, I've said that this ledger is in some public place,", "start": 613.02, "duration": 3.017}, {"text": "like a website where anyone can add new lines.", "start": 616.037, "duration": 2.403}, {"text": "But that would require trusting a central location, namely,", "start": 619.22, "duration": 3.531}, {"text": "who hosts the website, who controls the rules of adding new lines.", "start": 622.751, "duration": 4.009}, {"text": "To remove that bit of trust, we'll have everybody keep their own copy of the ledger.", "start": 627.34, "duration": 4.62}, {"text": "Then when you want to make a transaction, like Alice pays Bob 100 Ledger Dollars,", "start": 632.66, "duration": 4.587}, {"text": "what you do is broadcast that out into the world for people to", "start": 637.247, "duration": 3.568}, {"text": "hear and record on their own private ledgers.", "start": 640.815, "duration": 2.605}, {"text": "But unless you do something more, this system is absurdly bad.", "start": 644.84, "duration": 4.42}, {"text": "How could you get everyone to agree on what the right ledger is?", "start": 649.82, "duration": 2.92}, {"text": "When Bob receives a transaction, like Alice pays Bob 10 Ledger Dollars,", "start": 653.44, "duration": 3.799}, {"text": "how can he be sure that everyone else received and believes that same transaction?", "start": 657.239, "duration": 4.441}, {"text": "That he'll be able to later on go to Charlie and use", "start": 662.34, "duration": 2.43}, {"text": "those same 10 Ledger Dollars to make a transaction?", "start": 664.77, "duration": 2.43}, {"text": "Really, imagine yourself just listening to transactions being broadcast.", "start": 668.24, "duration": 3.82}, {"text": "How can you be sure that everyone else is recording", "start": 672.76, "duration": 2.901}, {"text": "the same transactions and in the same order?", "start": 675.661, "duration": 2.559}, {"text": "This is really the heart of the issue.", "start": 679.42, "duration": 1.94}, {"text": "This is an interesting puzzle.", "start": 681.6, "duration": 1.14}, {"text": "Can you come up with a protocol for how to accept or reject transactions,", "start": 683.42, "duration": 4.319}, {"text": "and in what order, so that you can feel confident that anyone else in the world", "start": 687.739, "duration": 4.733}, {"text": "who's following that same protocol has a personal ledger that looks the same as yours?", "start": 692.472, "duration": 5.148}, {"text": "This is the problem addressed in the original Bitcoin paper.", "start": 698.3, "duration": 3.28}, {"text": "At a high level, the solution that Bitcoin offers is to trust", "start": 704.06, "duration": 4.017}, {"text": "whichever ledger has the most computational work put into it.", "start": 708.077, "duration": 4.083}, {"text": "I'll take a moment to explain exactly what that means.", "start": 712.54, "duration": 2.32}, {"text": "It involves this thing called a cryptographic hash function.", "start": 715.32, "duration": 2.8}, {"text": "The general idea that we'll build to is that if you use computational work as a", "start": 718.46, "duration": 4.511}, {"text": "basis for what to trust, you can make it so that fraudulent transactions and", "start": 722.971, "duration": 4.398}, {"text": "conflicting ledgers would require an infeasible amount of computation to bring about.", "start": 727.369, "duration": 4.911}, {"text": "Again, I'll remind you that this is getting well into the weeds beyond", "start": 733.04, "duration": 3.391}, {"text": "what anyone would need to know just to use a currency like this.", "start": 736.431, "duration": 3.149}, {"text": "But it's a really cool idea, and if you understand it,", "start": 740.12, "duration": 2.764}, {"text": "you understand the heart of Bitcoin and other cryptocurrencies.", "start": 742.884, "duration": 3.276}, {"text": "So first things first, what's a hash function?", "start": 748.1, "duration": 1.84}, {"text": "The inputs for one of these functions can be any kind of message or file,", "start": 750.8, "duration": 3.961}, {"text": "it really doesn't matter. And the output is a string of bits", "start": 754.761, "duration": 3.309}, {"text": "with some kind of fixed length, like 256 bits.", "start": 758.07, "duration": 2.55}, {"text": "This output is called the hash or digest of the message,", "start": 761.18, "duration": 3.78}, {"text": "and the intent is that it looks random.", "start": 764.96, "duration": 2.7}, {"text": "It's not random, it always gives the same output for a given input.", "start": 768.0, "duration": 3.66}, {"text": "But the idea is that if you slightly change the input,", "start": 772.2, "duration": 3.16}, {"text": "maybe editing just one of the characters, the resulting hash changes completely.", "start": 775.36, "duration": 4.74}, {"text": "In fact, for the hash function I'm showing here, called SHA256,", "start": 780.82, "duration": 4.431}, {"text": "the way the output changes as you slightly change that input is entirely unpredictable.", "start": 785.251, "duration": 6.189}, {"text": "You see, this is not just any hash function, it's a cryptographic hash function.", "start": 792.44, "duration": 4.62}, {"text": "That means it's infeasible to compute in the reverse direction.", "start": 797.34, "duration": 3.32}, {"text": "If I show you some string of 1s and 0s, and ask you to find an input", "start": 801.26, "duration": 4.549}, {"text": "so that the SHA256 hash of that input gives this exact string of bits,", "start": 805.809, "duration": 4.75}, {"text": "you will have no better method than to just guess and check.", "start": 810.559, "duration": 4.081}, {"text": "And again, if you want to feel for how much computation would be needed to", "start": 815.7, "duration": 4.019}, {"text": "go through two to the 256 guesses, just take a look at the supplement video.", "start": 819.719, "duration": 4.181}, {"text": "I actually had way too much fun writing that thing.", "start": 824.38, "duration": 2.28}, {"text": "You might think that if you just really dig into the details of how exactly this function", "start": 828.56, "duration": 4.43}, {"text": "works, you could reverse engineer the appropriate input without having to guess and", "start": 832.99, "duration": 4.182}, {"text": "check.", "start": 837.172, "duration": 0.348}, {"text": "But no one has ever figured out a way to do that.", "start": 838.24, "duration": 2.6}, {"text": "Interestingly, there's no cold hard rigorous proof", "start": 841.6, "duration": 2.627}, {"text": "that it's hard to compute in the reverse direction.", "start": 844.227, "duration": 2.733}, {"text": "And yet, a huge amount of modern security depends on cryptographic", "start": 847.62, "duration": 3.502}, {"text": "hash functions and the idea that they have this property.", "start": 851.122, "duration": 3.078}, {"text": "If you were to look at what algorithms underlie the secure connection", "start": 854.94, "duration": 3.651}, {"text": "that your browser is making with YouTube right now,", "start": 858.591, "duration": 2.751}, {"text": "or that it makes with your bank, you'll likely see the name SHA256 show up in there.", "start": 861.342, "duration": 4.498}, {"text": "For right now, our focus will be on how such a function can prove that a particular", "start": 867.34, "duration": 4.919}, {"text": "list of transactions is associated with a large amount of computational effort.", "start": 872.259, "duration": 4.741}, {"text": "Imagine someone shows you a list of transactions, and they say, hey,", "start": 878.04, "duration": 4.053}, {"text": "I found a special number so that when you put that number at the end of this list of", "start": 882.093, "duration": 5.067}, {"text": "transactions, and apply SHA256 to the entire thing,", "start": 887.16, "duration": 3.099}, {"text": "the first 30 bits of that output are all zeros.", "start": 890.259, "duration": 2.861}, {"text": "How hard do you think it was for them to find that number?", "start": 894.1, "duration": 2.6}, {"text": "Well, for a random message, the probability that a hash happens to start", "start": 898.06, "duration": 4.407}, {"text": "with 30 successive zeros is 1 in 2 to the 30, which is about 1 in a billion.", "start": 902.467, "duration": 4.713}, {"text": "And because SHA256 is a cryptographic hash function,", "start": 908.2, "duration": 3.033}, {"text": "the only way to find a special number like that is just guessing and checking.", "start": 911.233, "duration": 4.607}, {"text": "So this person almost certainly had to go through about a", "start": 916.66, "duration": 2.811}, {"text": "billion different numbers before finding this special one.", "start": 919.471, "duration": 2.909}, {"text": "And once you know that number, it's really quick to verify,", "start": 923.38, "duration": 2.826}, {"text": "you just run the hash and see that there are 30 zeros.", "start": 926.206, "duration": 2.634}, {"text": "So in other words, you can verify that they went through a large amount of work,", "start": 929.8, "duration": 3.771}, {"text": "but without having to go through that same effort yourself.", "start": 933.571, "duration": 2.829}, {"text": "This is called a proof of work.", "start": 937.2, "duration": 1.6}, {"text": "And importantly, all of this work is intrinsically tied to the list of transactions.", "start": 939.46, "duration": 4.76}, {"text": "If you change one of those transactions, even slightly,", "start": 944.9, "duration": 2.834}, {"text": "it would completely change the hash.", "start": 947.734, "duration": 1.906}, {"text": "So you'd have to go through another billion guesses to find a new proof of work,", "start": 950.08, "duration": 4.294}, {"text": "a new number that makes it so that the hash of the altered list", "start": 954.374, "duration": 3.435}, {"text": "together with this new number starts with 30 zeros.", "start": 957.809, "duration": 2.791}, {"text": "So now think back to our distributed ledger situation.", "start": 961.5, "duration": 2.6}, {"text": "Everyone is there broadcasting transactions and we want", "start": 964.68, "duration": 3.08}, {"text": "a way for them to agree on what the correct ledger is.", "start": 967.76, "duration": 3.08}, {"text": "As I mentioned, the idea behind the original Bitcoin paper is to", "start": 972.1, "duration": 3.181}, {"text": "have everyone trust whichever ledger has the most work put into it.", "start": 975.281, "duration": 3.379}, {"text": "The way this works is to first organize a given ledger into blocks,", "start": 979.28, "duration": 3.573}, {"text": "where each block consists of a list of transactions together with a proof of work.", "start": 982.853, "duration": 4.427}, {"text": "That is, a special number so that the hash of", "start": 987.72, "duration": 2.265}, {"text": "the whole block starts with a bunch of zeros.", "start": 989.985, "duration": 2.315}, {"text": "For the moment, let's say it has to start with 60 zeros,", "start": 993.14, "duration": 2.99}, {"text": "but later we'll return back to a more systematic way you might want to choose", "start": 996.13, "duration": 4.164}, {"text": "that number. In the same way that a transaction is only considered valid when", "start": 1000.294, "duration": 4.164}, {"text": "it's signed by the sender,", "start": 1004.458, "duration": 1.442}, {"text": "a block is only considered valid if it has a proof of work.", "start": 1005.9, "duration": 4.14}, {"text": "Also, to make sure there's a standard order to these blocks,", "start": 1010.96, "duration": 3.377}, {"text": "we'll make it so that a block has to contain the hash of the previous block", "start": 1014.337, "duration": 4.279}, {"text": "at its header.", "start": 1018.616, "duration": 0.844}, {"text": "That way, if you were to go back and change any one of the blocks,", "start": 1020.06, "duration": 3.725}, {"text": "or to swap the order of two blocks, it would change the block that comes after it,", "start": 1023.785, "duration": 4.685}, {"text": "which changes that block's hash, which changes the one that comes after it, and so on.", "start": 1028.47, "duration": 4.91}, {"text": "That would require redoing all of the work, finding a new special number", "start": 1033.98, "duration": 3.772}, {"text": "for each of these blocks that makes their hashes start with 60 zeros.", "start": 1037.752, "duration": 3.668}, {"text": "Because blocks are chained together like this,", "start": 1042.44, "duration": 2.352}, {"text": "instead of calling it a ledger, it's common to call it a blockchain.", "start": 1044.792, "duration": 3.528}, {"text": "As part of our updated protocol, we'll now allow", "start": 1050.08, "duration": 2.289}, {"text": "anyone in the world to be a block creator.", "start": 1052.369, "duration": 2.051}, {"text": "What that means is that they're going to listen for transactions being broadcast,", "start": 1055.24, "duration": 3.931}, {"text": "collect them into some block, and then do a whole bunch of work to find a", "start": 1059.171, "duration": 3.592}, {"text": "special number that makes the hash of that block start with 60 zeros.", "start": 1062.763, "duration": 3.397}, {"text": "Once they find it, they broadcast out the block they found.", "start": 1066.96, "duration": 2.94}, {"text": "To reward a block creator for all this work, when she puts together a block,", "start": 1070.86, "duration": 4.288}, {"text": "we'll allow her to include a very special transaction at the top of it,", "start": 1075.148, "duration": 4.063}, {"text": "in which she gets, say, 10 ledger dollars out of thin air.", "start": 1079.211, "duration": 3.329}, {"text": "This is called the block reward, and it's an exception to", "start": 1083.08, "duration": 3.053}, {"text": "our usual rules about whether or not to accept transactions.", "start": 1086.133, "duration": 3.267}, {"text": "It doesn't come from anyone, so it doesn't have to be signed.", "start": 1090.04, "duration": 2.88}, {"text": "It also means that the total number of ledger", "start": 1093.66, "duration": 2.709}, {"text": "dollars in our economy increases with each new block.", "start": 1096.369, "duration": 3.251}, {"text": "Creating blocks is often called mining, since it requires doing a lot of work,", "start": 1100.9, "duration": 4.206}, {"text": "and it introduces new bits of currency into the economy.", "start": 1105.106, "duration": 3.074}, {"text": "But when you hear or read about miners, keep in mind that what they're", "start": 1109.02, "duration": 4.012}, {"text": "really doing is listening for transactions, creating blocks,", "start": 1113.032, "duration": 3.495}, {"text": "broadcasting those blocks, and getting rewarded with new money for doing so.", "start": 1116.527, "duration": 4.413}, {"text": "From the miners' perspective, each block is like a miniature lottery,", "start": 1121.78, "duration": 3.87}, {"text": "where everyone is guessing numbers as fast as they can,", "start": 1125.65, "duration": 3.142}, {"text": "until one lucky individual finds a special number that makes the hash of the block", "start": 1128.792, "duration": 4.656}, {"text": "start with many zeros, and they get the reward.", "start": 1133.448, "duration": 2.692}, {"text": "For anyone else who just wants to use this system to make payments,", "start": 1137.62, "duration": 3.46}, {"text": "instead of listening for transactions, they all start listening just for blocks", "start": 1141.08, "duration": 4.131}, {"text": "being broadcast by miners, and updating their own personal copies of the blockchain.", "start": 1145.211, "duration": 4.389}, {"text": "Now the key addition to our protocol is that if you hear two", "start": 1150.56, "duration": 3.688}, {"text": "distinct blockchains with conflicting transaction histories,", "start": 1154.248, "duration": 3.749}, {"text": "you defer to the longest one, the one with the most work put into it.", "start": 1157.997, "duration": 4.303}, {"text": "If there's a tie, just wait until you hear an", "start": 1162.86, "duration": 2.352}, {"text": "additional block that makes one of them longer.", "start": 1165.212, "duration": 2.508}, {"text": "So even though there's no central authority, and everyone is maintaining their own", "start": 1168.72, "duration": 4.548}, {"text": "copy of the blockchain, if everyone agrees to give preference to whichever blockchain", "start": 1173.268, "duration": 4.769}, {"text": "has the most work put into it, we have a way to arrive at decentralized consensus.", "start": 1178.037, "duration": 4.603}, {"text": "To see why this makes for a trustworthy system,", "start": 1183.56, "duration": 2.292}, {"text": "and to understand at what point you should trust that a payment is legit,", "start": 1185.852, "duration": 3.609}, {"text": "it's actually really helpful to walk through exactly what it would take to", "start": 1189.461, "duration": 3.658}, {"text": "fool someone using this system.", "start": 1193.119, "duration": 1.561}, {"text": "Maybe Alice is trying to fool Bob with a fraudulent block,", "start": 1195.6, "duration": 3.311}, {"text": "namely she tries to send him one that includes her paying him 100 Ledger dollars,", "start": 1198.911, "duration": 4.68}, {"text": "but without broadcasting that block to the rest of the network,", "start": 1203.591, "duration": 3.653}, {"text": "that way everyone else still thinks she has those 100 Ledger dollars.", "start": 1207.244, "duration": 3.996}, {"text": "To do this, she would have to find a valid proof of work before all the other miners,", "start": 1211.96, "duration": 4.841}, {"text": "each working on their own block.", "start": 1216.801, "duration": 1.879}, {"text": "And that could definitely happen, maybe Alice just happens", "start": 1219.5, "duration": 2.805}, {"text": "to win this miniature lottery before everyone else.", "start": 1222.305, "duration": 2.515}, {"text": "But Bob is still going to be hearing the broadcasts made by other miners,", "start": 1225.68, "duration": 4.001}, {"text": "so to keep him believing this fraudulent block,", "start": 1229.681, "duration": 2.632}, {"text": "Alice would have to do all the work herself to keep adding blocks on this", "start": 1232.313, "duration": 4.056}, {"text": "special fork in Bob's blockchain that's different from what he's hearing", "start": 1236.369, "duration": 4.001}, {"text": "from the rest of the miners.", "start": 1240.37, "duration": 1.59}, {"text": "Remember, as per the protocol, Bob always trusts the longest chain he knows about.", "start": 1242.74, "duration": 5.52}, {"text": "Alice might be able to keep this up for a few blocks if just by chance she finds", "start": 1249.26, "duration": 4.301}, {"text": "blocks more quickly than the rest of the miners on the network all combined.", "start": 1253.561, "duration": 4.139}, {"text": "But unless she has close to 50% of the computing resources among all of the miners,", "start": 1258.48, "duration": 4.941}, {"text": "the probability becomes overwhelming that the blockchain that all the other miners", "start": 1263.421, "duration": 4.941}, {"text": "are working on grows faster than the single fraudulent blockchain Alice is feeding to", "start": 1268.362, "duration": 5.12}, {"text": "Bob.", "start": 1273.482, "duration": 0.298}, {"text": "So after enough time, Bob will just reject what he's hearing from", "start": 1275.0, "duration": 3.949}, {"text": "Alice in favor of the longer chain that everyone else is working on.", "start": 1278.949, "duration": 4.191}, {"text": "Notice, that means you shouldn't necessarily trust a new block you hear immediately.", "start": 1283.96, "duration": 4.96}, {"text": "Instead, you should wait for several new blocks to be added on top of it.", "start": 1289.5, "duration": 3.9}, {"text": "If you still haven't heard of any longer blockchains,", "start": 1293.82, "duration": 2.581}, {"text": "you can trust that this block is part of the same chain that everyone else is using.", "start": 1296.401, "duration": 4.139}, {"text": "And with that, we've hit all the main ideas.", "start": 1302.12, "duration": 3.1}, {"text": "This distributed ledger system based on a proof of work is more or less", "start": 1305.78, "duration": 3.868}, {"text": "how the Bitcoin protocol works, and how many other cryptocurrencies work.", "start": 1309.648, "duration": 4.032}, {"text": "There's just a few details to clear up.", "start": 1314.3, "duration": 1.86}, {"text": "Earlier I said that the proof of work might be to find a special", "start": 1316.3, "duration": 3.268}, {"text": "number so that the hash of the block starts with 60 zeros.", "start": 1319.568, "duration": 3.012}, {"text": "Well, the way the actual Bitcoin protocol works is to periodically change that", "start": 1323.22, "duration": 4.179}, {"text": "number of zeros so that it should take, on average, 10 minutes to find a new block.", "start": 1327.399, "duration": 4.501}, {"text": "So as there are more and more miners added to the network,", "start": 1332.78, "duration": 3.262}, {"text": "the challenge gets harder and harder in such a way that this", "start": 1336.042, "duration": 3.431}, {"text": "miniature lottery only has about one winner every 10 minutes.", "start": 1339.473, "duration": 3.487}, {"text": "Many newer cryptocurrencies have much shorter block times than that.", "start": 1343.92, "duration": 3.96}, {"text": "And all of the money in Bitcoin ultimately comes from some block reward.", "start": 1348.58, "duration": 3.88}, {"text": "In the beginning, these rewards were 50 Bitcoin per block.", "start": 1352.92, "duration": 2.82}, {"text": "There's actually a great website you can go to called Block", "start": 1356.14, "duration": 2.453}, {"text": "Explorer that makes it easy to look through the Bitcoin blockchain.", "start": 1358.593, "duration": 2.827}, {"text": "And if you look at the very first few blocks on the chain,", "start": 1361.96, "duration": 3.128}, {"text": "they contain no transactions other than that 50 Bitcoin reward to the miner.", "start": 1365.088, "duration": 4.152}, {"text": "But every 210,000 blocks, which is about every 4 years, that reward gets cut in half.", "start": 1369.86, "duration": 6.48}, {"text": "So right now, the reward is 12.5 Bitcoin per block.", "start": 1376.86, "duration": 3.28}, {"text": "And because this reward decreases geometrically over time,", "start": 1380.72, "duration": 3.837}, {"text": "it means there will never be more than 21 million Bitcoin in existence.", "start": 1384.557, "duration": 4.763}, {"text": "However, this doesn't mean miners will stop earning money.", "start": 1390.28, "duration": 3.0}, {"text": "In addition to the block reward, miners can also pick up transaction fees.", "start": 1393.82, "duration": 4.12}, {"text": "The way this works is that whenever you make a payment,", "start": 1398.52, "duration": 2.921}, {"text": "you can purely optionally include a transaction fee with it", "start": 1401.441, "duration": 3.187}, {"text": "that will go to the miner of whichever block includes that payment.", "start": 1404.628, "duration": 3.612}, {"text": "The reason you might do that is to incentivize miners to actually", "start": 1409.02, "duration": 3.617}, {"text": "include the transaction you broadcast into the next block.", "start": 1412.637, "duration": 3.283}, {"text": "You see, in Bitcoin, each block is limited to about 2400 transactions,", "start": 1416.44, "duration": 4.805}, {"text": "which many critics argue is unnecessarily restrictive.", "start": 1421.245, "duration": 3.775}, {"text": "For comparison, Visa processes an average of about 1700 transactions per second,", "start": 1425.86, "duration": 5.367}, {"text": "and they're capable of handling more than 24,000 per second.", "start": 1431.227, "duration": 4.093}, {"text": "This comparatively slow processing on Bitcoin makes for higher transaction fees,", "start": 1436.02, "duration": 4.819}, {"text": "since that's what determines which transactions miners choose to include in a new block.", "start": 1440.839, "duration": 5.361}, {"text": "All of this is far from a comprehensive coverage of cryptocurrencies.", "start": 1447.82, "duration": 3.68}, {"text": "There are still many nuances and alternate design choices that I haven't even touched.", "start": 1452.16, "duration": 4.02}, {"text": "But my hope is that this can provide a stable WaitButWhy-style tree-trunk of", "start": 1456.64, "duration": 3.713}, {"text": "understanding for anyone looking to add a few more branches with further reading.", "start": 1460.353, "duration": 4.007}, {"text": "Like I said at the start, one of the motives behind this is that a lot of money has", "start": 1465.18, "duration": 3.744}, {"text": "started flowing towards cryptocurrencies, and even though I don't want to make any", "start": 1468.924, "duration": 3.743}, {"text": "claims about whether that's a good or bad investment,", "start": 1472.667, "duration": 2.436}, {"text": "I really do think it's healthy for people getting into the game to at least know the", "start": 1475.103, "duration": 3.834}, {"text": "fundamentals of the technology.", "start": 1478.937, "duration": 1.443}, {"text": "As always, my sincerest thanks to those of you making this channel possible on Patreon.", "start": 1481.34, "duration": 4.08}, {"text": "I understand that not everyone is in a position to contribute,", "start": 1486.08, "duration": 2.91}, {"text": "but if you're still interested in helping out,", "start": 1488.99, "duration": 2.206}, {"text": "one of the best ways to do that is simply to share videos that you think", "start": 1491.196, "duration": 3.426}, {"text": "might be interesting or helpful to others.", "start": 1494.622, "duration": 2.018}, {"text": "I know you know that, but it really does help.", "start": 1497.28, "duration": 2.04}]
